            "id": "4578584",
            "title": "Dover tops Q1 estimates as broad industrial demand lifts results",
            "description": "<html><body><p class=\"MsoNormal\" data-eci=\"true\">Dover (<span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\"><a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/DOV\" title=\"Dover Corporation\">DOV</a></span>), the diversified industrial manufacturer, <a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/news/4578524-dover-non-gaap-eps-of-2_28-beats-by-0_01-revenue-of-2_05b-beats-by-50m\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"reported\">reported</a> results on Thursday that topped Wall Street expectations for revenue and earnings.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Shares of Dover (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/DOV\" title=\"Dover Corporation\">DOV</a>) were little changed in premarket trading. As of Wednesday’s close, the stock was up 32% over the prior 12 months.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Revenue rose 10% to $2.05 billion from $1.87 billion a year earlier, beating analysts’ consensus estimate of $2.0 billion. Adjusted diluted earnings per share rose 11% to $2.28, ahead of estimates of $2.27 a share.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Net income rose to $238.4 million, or $1.75 a share, from $230.8 million, or $1.67 a share, a year earlier.</p>\n<h3 class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Orders signal momentum</strong></h3>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">“We delivered a solid start to the year, with double-digit revenue growth driven by continued strength in our secular-growth-exposed end markets and improving conditions across the portfolio,” Chief Executive Richard Tobin said in the earnings release.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Tobin added that booking rates were strong, with book-to-bill above one in all five operating segments, pointing to healthy demand and improved visibility for the rest of 2026.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Total consolidated bookings climbed to $2.46 billion from $1.99 billion a year earlier.</p>\n<h3 class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Standout segments include fueling, climate</strong></h3>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Clean energy and fueling revenue rose 13% to $554.8 million, supported by demand for retail fueling systems and clean-energy infrastructure. Climate and sustainability technologies revenue jumped 18% to $411.1 million, benefiting from strong heat exchanger and thermal-management demand.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Pumps and process solutions, one of Dover (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/DOV\" title=\"Dover Corporation\">DOV</a>)’s most profitable units, increased sales 9% to $537.8 million and posted a segment margin of 31.5%.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Imaging and identification revenue was more modest, rising 2% to $285.4 million.</p>\n<h3 class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong>Cash flow and outlook hold firm</strong></h3>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Dover (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/DOV\" title=\"Dover Corporation\">DOV</a>) generated $191 million in operating cash flow, up from $157 million a year earlier. Free cash flow rose to $131 million from $109 million.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">The company reaffirmed its full-year 2026 outlook, forecasting revenue growth of 5% to 7%, including 3% to 5% organic growth, with GAAP earnings per share of $8.92 to $9.12 and adjusted earnings per share of $10.45 to $10.65, compared with the consensus estimate of $10.58 for the adjusted figure.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Dover (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/DOV\" title=\"Dover Corporation\">DOV</a>) owns a broad portfolio of industrial brands including OPW fueling equipment, Wayne fuel dispensers, Belvac packaging machinery, Markem-Imaje coding systems, CPC quick-connect components and SWEP heat exchangers. Its products are widely used in convenience stores, factories, food packaging, data centers and climate-control systems.</p>\n<div class=\"signup_widget_placeholder\"></div>\n</body></html>",
